\begin_layout Subsection
Survival selection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that survival selection 
\begin_inset Formula $S(u,\theta_{i})$
\end_inset

 of adults is given by the function (see also eqns.
 [1,2] in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Leimar2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
S\left(u,\theta_{i}\right) & =\begin{cases}
1-0.8u^{2} & \theta_{i}=\theta_{\mathrm{low}}\\
1-0.8\left(1-u\right)^{2} & \theta_{i}=\theta_{\mathrm{high}}
\end{cases},\label{eq:supplement:survival_selection}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is the function depicted in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

B.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Juvenile phenotype determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recap from the main text, the juvenile phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 that is developed after individual learning is a logistic function of a
 weighted sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 of different cues an individual has received.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{\mathrm{juv}} & =\frac{1}{1+\exp\left(-\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}\right)}\label{eq:supplement:liability}\\
\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}} & =a_{\mathrm{g}}x_{\mathrm{gen}}+a_{\mathrm{\mathrm{ind}}}x_{\mathrm{ind}}\nonumber \\
 & +m_{\mathrm{m}}x_{\mathrm{mat,phen}}+m_{\mathrm{e}}x_{\mathrm{mat,envt}}\nonumber \\
 & +v_{\mathrm{p}}x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}+v_{c}x_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}},\label{eq:supplement:xbar:juvenile}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

s in the equation above are the values of each of the different cues, each
 of which is weighed by a sensitivity locus that can flexibly evolve.
 Regarding the evolving sensitivity loci, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{g}}$
\end_inset

 is the sensitivity to the genetic cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{gen}}$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:supplement:Genetic-cues"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 The locus 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{ind}}$
\end_inset

 reflects evolving sensitivity to individually learned cues 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{ind}}$
\end_inset

 that inform about the state of local environment at birth (see section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:supplement:Individually-learned-cues"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 The locus 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 reflects evolving sensitivity to the maternal phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{mat,phen}}$
\end_inset

 as a cue, while the locus 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{e}}$
\end_inset

 reflects evolving sensitivity to the maternal environment 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{mat,envt}}$
\end_inset

 as a cue (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:supplement:Maternal-cues"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Finally, the juvenile phenotype is also influenced by vertical social learning:
 here, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 reflects evolving sensitivity to vertically learned phenotypic cues based
 on prestige biases 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{vert,\mathrm{prestige}}}$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:supplement:Vertical-social-prestige"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The locus 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 reflects evolving sensitivity to vertically learned phenotypic cues based
 on conformity biases (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:supplement:Vertical-social-prestige"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Genetic cues
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:supplement:Genetic-cues"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following similar models by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Leimar2006,Leimar2015,Leimar2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the value of the genetic cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{gen}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{gen}}=\sum_{i=0}^{n_{\mathrm{g}}}g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, it is the sum of the allelic values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{g}}=3$
\end_inset

 unlinked, diploid genetic cue loci 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Each allele can have values in the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq g_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, limited dispersal can result in scenarios where alleles become
 associated with the local environment, so that alleles become informative.
 Note that alleles of the genetic cue themselves are not involved in local
 adaptation, they purely have an informational function.
 The role of genetic cues is further discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dall2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Individually learned cues
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:supplement:Individually-learned-cues"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Juveniles perform individual learning about the state of their local environment
s by observing a juvenile environmental cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{ind}}$
\end_inset

.
 To this end, each individual independently observes a binary cue reflecting
 the state of the local environment.
 The cue is equal to the actual environmental state (value 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{low}}$
\end_inset

, value 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

) with a probability given by the cue fidelity parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\leq q_{\mathrm{juv}}\leq1$
\end_inset

, whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 an individual receives a cue associated with the opposite environmental
 state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Maternal cues
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:supplement:Maternal-cues"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Juveniles receive two maternal cues: the first is a maternal phenotypic
 cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{mat,phen}}=u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)-1/2$
\end_inset

 that reflects the value of the maternal phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 By subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)$
\end_inset

 we standardise the maternal phenotype between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 so that the maternal phenotypic cue has the same range as other plastic
 cues (and hence evolved cue sensitivities can be directly compared).
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)$
\end_inset

 is itself a function of her mother's phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-2)$
\end_inset

 (a so-called cascading parental effect: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kirkpatrick1989,McGlothlin2013,Kuijper2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), a maternal phenotypic cue can potentially give rise to grandmaternal
 effects.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Leimar2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an assessment of noise in maternal phenotypic cues, which we do not
 consider here for the sake of brevity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second maternal cue is a maternal environmental cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{mat,envt}}$
\end_inset

, which reflects the value of the maternal environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rossiter1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as provided to the mother by the adult environmental cue (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The cue is equal to the actual environmental state (value 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{low}}$
\end_inset

, value 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

) with a probability given by the cue fidelity parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\leq q_{\mathrm{mat}}\leq1$
\end_inset

, whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{\mathrm{mat}}$
\end_inset

 an individual receives a cue associated with the opposite environmental
 state.
 We assume that all offspring born form the same mother obtain the same
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{mat,envt}}$
\end_inset

 (i.e., errors act at the level of the brood, rather than at the level of
 the individual offspring).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vertical social learning: prestige biases
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:supplement:Vertical-social-prestige"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following previous models of prestige-based learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Henrich2004,Kobayashi2012a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we assume that individuals are able to evaluate and rank the performance
 of observed models.
 To this end, learners rank the potential survival payoffs 
\begin_inset Formula $S(u_{\mathrm{ad},i})$
\end_inset

 of each individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in a random sample of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 adult models after survival selection has taken place in the previous generatio
n (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The potential survival payoff is evaluated based on 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th model's adult phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad},i}$
\end_inset

 that is observed by the learner (see eq.
 [
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

] below) in the learner's environment at time of birth (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 is then a function of the phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad},\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset

 of the sampled individual which has the highest ranked survivorship value,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}=u_{\mathrm{ad},\mathrm{max}}+\xi_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}-1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 is a sample drawn from a Gaussian noise distribution with mean 0 and standard
 deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}$
\end_inset

, and subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 standardises the cue range to the same scale as for other cues.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vertical social learning: conformity-biases
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:supplement:Vertical-social-conformity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We follow previous models of conformity-based social learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Eriksson2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where individuals evaluate phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 of each individual belonging to randomly chosen subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 surviving adult models from the parental generation in the local patch.
 Individuals take account of the number of individuals 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}\leq n_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 with a phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the low environment (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}<0.5$
\end_inset

), whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}=n_{\mathrm{c}}-n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}$
\end_inset

 reflects the number of individuals with phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\geq0.5$
\end_inset

.
 We then have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}} & =\begin{cases}
-1/2 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}>n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{ (low-matching phenotype predominates)}\\
0 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}=n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{\text{ (no phenotype predominates)}}\\
1/2 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}<n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{\text{ (high-matching phenotype predominates)}}
\end{cases}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Moreover, we add noise to the cue by adding a random deviate from a Gaussian
 distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}}$
\end_inset

.
 We have also considered alternative configurations where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}}=n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}/(n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}+n_{\mathrm{c,lo}})$
\end_inset

, but these give similar results (results not shown).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Adult phenotype determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recap from the main text, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{\mathrm{ad}} & =\frac{1}{1+\exp\left(-\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}}\right)}\label{eq:supplement:liability:adult}\\
\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}} & =\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}+h_{\mathrm{p}}x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}+h_{c}x_{\mathrm{horiz,conformity}},\label{eq:supplement:xbar:adult}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 (horizontal social learning; prestige bias) and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 (horizontal social learning; conformity bias) again reflect unlinked and
 evolving diploid loci (bounded between [-10,10]) that reflect sensitivity
 to both horizontally learned social cues 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{horiz,}\text{conformity}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

